  <h1>What to Do Before Signing a Severance Agreement</h1>
  <p class="byline">By <strong>our editorial team</strong>. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    You've been handed a severance agreement. It's dense, it's in legalese, and HR is asking when you'll have it back. The pressure to sign quickly — to end the discomfort, take the money, and move on — is real. Resist it. The review period is the last moment of leverage you have in your employment relationship. Here's what to do with it.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Know Your Review Period Rights</h2>
  <p>
    Under the Age Discrimination in Employment Act (ADEA), as amended by the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act (OWBPA), employees aged <strong>40 or older</strong> are entitled to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>At least <strong>21 days</strong> to review an individual severance agreement (45 days for group layoffs)</li>
    <li>A <strong>7-day revocation period</strong> after signing — you can change your mind within 7 days of signing and the agreement becomes void</li>
    <li>Written notice of which positions were selected for the layoff and which were not (for group reductions), so you can assess whether age discrimination may have played a role</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Employees under 40 are not entitled to these minimum periods by federal law, but most employers provide a deadline (often 14 or 21 days) in the agreement itself. That deadline is generally negotiable if you need more time to consult an attorney.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Read the Entire Agreement — Including the Fine Print</h2>
  <p>
    It sounds obvious, but many people sign agreements they haven't fully read, assuming it's "standard." Agreements vary widely. At a minimum, identify:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The consideration:</strong> Exactly what you're receiving — cash amount, payment schedule, benefit continuation, outplacement services. Confirm it matches what was described verbally.</li>
    <li><strong>The release of claims:</strong> What legal claims you are giving up. A "general release" typically waives all employment-related claims, including discrimination, harassment, retaliation, wage violations, and FMLA. Some releases also include a waiver of WARN Act claims — note this specifically.</li>
    <li><strong>Carve-outs:</strong> What the release does NOT cover. OWBPA requires that waivers of ADEA (age discrimination) claims meet specific requirements to be enforceable. Most agreements also preserve your right to file a charge with the EEOC, even if you waive the right to sue.</li>
    <li><strong>Non-compete and non-solicitation:</strong> Scope, duration, geography, and covered activities. See section below.</li>
    <li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> What you are prohibited from disclosing, to whom, and for how long. Some confidentiality clauses are so broad they prohibit you from discussing the circumstances of your termination with anyone — including your own attorney.</li>
    <li><strong>Non-disparagement:</strong> Whether it is one-way (only you are bound) or mutual (employer is also bound). A one-way clause protects only the company; push for mutual language.</li>
    <li><strong>Clawback provisions:</strong> What triggers recapture of paid severance. Common triggers: breach of confidentiality, violation of non-compete, re-employment by the company within a defined period.</li>
    <li><strong>Cooperation clause:</strong> Whether you're obligated to assist with litigation or government investigations after your departure. Understand the scope and whether you'll be compensated for time spent.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>3. Evaluate the Non-Compete Carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Non-competes included in severance agreements deserve particular scrutiny. Unlike non-competes signed at the start of employment (where the job offer itself is the consideration), a severance non-compete needs to be supported by "adequate consideration" — the severance itself. Courts in many states will analyze whether the severance payment was adequate to justify the restriction being imposed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key questions to ask about any non-compete:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>How long does it last? (6–12 months is more defensible than 2 years; anything beyond 2 years is a red flag in most states)</li>
    <li>How broad is the geography? (national or international restrictions are frequently unenforceable)</li>
    <li>What activities are restricted? (working for a "competitor" is vague; "performing substantially similar duties for companies that derive more than X% of revenue from [defined product category]" is specific and defensible)</li>
    <li>What state's law governs? (California, Minnesota, and North Dakota nearly always void non-competes for employees; a California-based employee working for a California-based employer has strong grounds to refuse this clause)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the non-compete is overly broad or would materially impair your ability to find new work in your field, negotiate to narrow it before signing — or consult an attorney about its enforceability in your state.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Consult an Employment Attorney</h2>
  <p>
    For any severance package of meaningful size (and especially any package above $25,000), a one-hour attorney consultation is worth the investment. An employment attorney can:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Identify potential legal claims that give you leverage to negotiate a higher package</li>
    <li>Flag problematic clauses you might not have noticed (overbroad confidentiality, problematic cooperation requirements, inadequate ADEA waiver language)</li>
    <li>Advise on the enforceability of the non-compete in your state</li>
    <li>Confirm whether the OWBPA requirements are actually met for the ADEA waiver to be valid</li>
    <li>Help you craft a negotiation strategy and written counter-proposal</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many employment attorneys offer flat-fee severance review services ($200–$600 is typical for a review and one round of negotiation advice). It's a fraction of one week's additional severance.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Negotiate Before You Sign</h2>
  <p>
    The time to negotiate is now — before your signature. Once you sign the release of claims, your leverage is gone. Common items worth negotiating in the agreement itself:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Add a mutual non-disparagement clause if only a one-way version was offered</li>
    <li>Narrow the non-compete scope, duration, or geography</li>
    <li>Add a neutral reference policy (agreed-upon language HR will use when called)</li>
    <li>Confirm the exact date your benefits end and whether COBRA subsidy is included</li>
    <li>Request a "rehire" provision — that your departure is classified as eligible for future rehire</li>
    <li>Clarify that the cooperation clause requires only reasonable time and includes reimbursement for expenses</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>6. Understand What You're Giving Up</h2>
  <p>
    A general release is not a formality — it is a final settlement of all legal claims arising from your employment. Before you sign, honestly assess: Do I believe I was discriminated against? Was I retaliated against for reporting misconduct? Were my wages correctly calculated and paid? Did my employer deny protected leave I was entitled to under FMLA or state law?
  </p>
  <p>
    If the answer to any of these is yes — or even possibly yes — the value of those potential claims should factor into whether the severance offer is adequate compensation for releasing them. An employment attorney can help you estimate the value of potential claims vs. the certainty of the offered severance.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This checklist is for general informational purposes only and is not legal advice. Every severance agreement is different, and individual rights vary by state, agreement terms, and circumstances. Consult a licensed employment attorney before signing any separation agreement.
  </p>
